{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17648285","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17648285"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T20:53:15+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T20:53:15+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18307"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18307","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18307"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.16,0.23,0.03,0.48,0.1]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11025"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78522"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11025","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11025"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18307"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63863"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"7236"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"25586"},{"type":"contributions","id":"25587"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26898"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78522","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/78522"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe sciatic nerve is in close proximity to a number of muscles as it runs from the pelvis down into the lower limb.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following muscles is located on the anterior surface of the sciatic nerve as it forms in the true pelvis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Adductor magnus","Gluteus medius","Gracilis","Piriformis","Quadratus femoris"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe sciatic nerve is the largest nerve in the human body and is a major nerve of the lower limb. It originates in the pelvis and travels through the gluteal region into the posterior thigh.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe sciatic nerve forms on the anterior surface of the \u003Cstrong\u003Epiriformis\u003C/strong\u003E muscle in the true pelvis. The piriformis is a key landmark in the gluteal region, and the sciatic nerve typically exits the pelvis below this muscle.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EQuadratus femoris\u003C/strong\u003E - This muscle is located in the posterior hip region but does not relate to the formation of the sciatic nerve\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAdductor magnus\u003C/strong\u003E - This muscle is located in the medial thigh and is not involved in the formation of the sciatic nerve\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGluteus medius\u003C/strong\u003E - This muscle is located in the lateral hip region and is not associated with the sciatic nerve\u0027s formation\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGracilis\u003C/strong\u003E - This muscle is located in the medial thigh and does not relate to the sciatic nerve\u0027s formation\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The sciatic nerve forms in the true pelvis on the anterior surface of the piriformis muscle.","The sciatic nerve is the largest nerve in the human body and is a major nerve of the lower limb.","The piriformis muscle is located in the gluteal region and plays a role in the lateral rotation of the hip."],"references":["Sud, A., \u0026 Ranjan, R. (2018). Textbook of Orthopaedics, -E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Singh, V. (2018). Textbook of Anatomy Abdomen and Lower Limb; Volume II (Vol. 2). Elsevier Health Sciences","Cantrell AJ, Imonugo O, Varacallo M. Anatomy, Bony Pelvis and Lower Limb: Leg Bones. [Updated 2023 Aug 14]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK537024/","Raftery A. General Anatomy and Musculoskeletal System. Ann R Coll Surg Engl. 2006 Jul;88(4):425. doi: 10.1308/003588406X114802d. PMCID: PMC1964629","Chaudhry SR, Nahian A, Chaudhry K. Anatomy, Abdomen and Pelvis, Pelvis. [Updated 2023 Jul 25]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK482258/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63863"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18307"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63863","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/63863"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-11T09:14:45+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-11T09:15:26+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11025"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78522"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"7